com.alexgilleran.icesoap.xpath.elements

Interface XPathElement

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Cloneable
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AttributeXPathElement, BaseXPathElement, DoubleSlashXPathElement, RelativeXPathElement, SingleSlashXPathElement

    public interface XPathElement
extends Cloneable
    Represents a single element in an xpath expression. E.g. in the xpath " this//is/an/@xpath", "this", "is", " an" and "@xpath" would all be XPathElements of various types.

    Within IceSoap there is no holistic "XPath" type - rather, an XPath as a whole is represented by its last element. Hence, if someone wanted to determine whether one XPath expression matched another, they would find the XPathElement instance representing the final element of each and execute the matches operation.

    Author:
    Alex Gilleran

  • addPredicate

    void addPredicate(String name,
                String value)

    Adds a predicate to this XPath element. Currently, any predicates added will act as "and" rather than "or" when matching with another elements.

    e.g. In the XPath expression /xpath/example[@predname="predvalue"], "predname" would be the name passed into this operation, and "predvalue" would be the value.

    Parameters:
    name - The name of the predicate.
    value - The value for the predicate.

  • matches

    boolean matches(XPathElement otherElement)

    Determines whether the passed XPathElement matches all the information specified by this one.

    Note that this operation does not work the same in both directions like .equals. For instance, if I call

    xpathElementA.matches(xpathElementB)

    Then I'm querying whether xpathElementB matches everything specified by xpathElementB. So if xpathElementB is horrendously complicated like

    /this[@pred="value"]/is/a[@anotherpred="anothervalue" and @yetanotherpred="yetanothervalue"]/very/complicated/xpath

    but xpathElementA is something very simple like

    //xpath

    xpathElementA.matches(xpathElementB) will return true. In this case, xpathElementB.matches(xpathElementA) will return false.

    Parameters:
    otherElement - Another element to try to match.
    Returns:
    Whether the passed element matches all the information represented by this xpath.

  • isFirstElement

    boolean isFirstElement()
    Determines whether this element is the first in the XPath expression. E.g. in the XPath expression /example/xpath, invoking isFirstElement() on the example element will return true, whereas on the xpath node it will return false.
    Returns:
    true if the first element, otherwise false.

  • setPreviousElement

    void setPreviousElement(XPathElement previousElement)

    Sets the previous element to this one in the XPath expression. Note that an xpath element will retain the behaviour determined by how many slashes prefix it.

    E.g. If I have an XPath //allnode/xpath and set allnode's previous element as /element, the resulting entire XPath will be /element//allnode/xpath.

    Note that for relative XPaths, setting a previous element changes it to a standard single-slash XPath element. E.g. if I have a relative xpath allnode/xpath and set allnode's previous element to /element as above, the resulting entire XPath will become /element/allnode/xpath.

    Parameters:
    previousElement - The element to set as the previous element to this one.
